164. Aequis. In the sense of Propitiis—165. Porcum. As all the good and bad accidents that happened in families were generally attributed to the household deities, Stertinius advises the man who, by the favour of these gods, is neither perjured nor a miser, gratefully to sacrifice a hog to them, which was their usual oblation.—166. Naviget Anticyram. Compare note on verse 83. The expression naviyet Anticyram (or Anticyras) is one of a proverbial character, and equivalent to “insanus est.”-Barathro. “ On the greedy and all-devouring gulf of the popu- lace.''
